{{about|trustless decentralized applications|other types of decentralized applications|distributed computing}} A '''decentralized application''' ('''Dapp''', '''dApp''' or '''DApp''') is an [[application software|application]] run by many users on a [[distributed computing|decentralized network]] with trustless [[cryptographic protocols|protocols]]. They are designed to avoid any single point of failure.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} They typically have tokens to reward users for providing computing power.{{r|coinwhat}}{{Unreliable source?|reason=non-RS, two-person blog|certain=y|date=October 2018}}
==Definition== The definition of a decentralized application is still in development and under debate.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} The term originates from the Decentralized Application Corporation and [[decentralized autonomous organization]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/953971624|title=Decentralized applications: Harnessing Bitcoin's Blockchain technology|last=Siraj|first=Raval|publisher=O'Reilly Media|year=2016|isbn=9781491924525|edition= First|location=Sebastopol, CA|pages=|oclc=953971624}}</ref>{{r|sr|p1=1-8}}
Typical definitions include the following attributes:<ref name=":0" />{{r|sr|p4=1-8}}<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/DavidJohnstonCEO/DecentralizedApplication|title=The General Theory of Decentralized Applications, Dapps|last=Johnston|first=David|last2=Yilmaz|first2=Sam Onat|date=2 February 2015|website=GitHub|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=23 November 2018|last3=Kandah|first3=Jeremy|last4=Bentenitis|first4=Nikos|last5=Hashemi|first5=Farzad|last6=Gross|first6=Ron|last7=Wilkinson|first7=Shawn|last8=Mason|first8=Steven}}</ref><ref name="blockchainhub">{{cite web |title=Decentralized Applications – dApps |url=https://blockchainhub.net/decentralized-applications-dapps/ |website=Blockchain Hub |accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref><ref name="ruth">{{cite web |last1=Ruth |first1=Angela |title=Why Build Decentralized Applications: Understanding Dapp |url=https://due.com/blog/why-build-decentralized-applications-understanding-dapp/ |website=Due |accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Demchenko |first1=Lidiia |title=Why People Choose Dapps over Apps? |url=https://www.dapp.com/article/why-people-choose-dapps-over-apps |website=Dapp |accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref> * The code is [[open-source]] and autonomously managed * Records and data are stored using [[blockchain]], providing trustless interaction and avoiding any single point of failure * Use [[cryptographic token]]s as a medium of exchange, to reward users validating transactions or providing services on the network, etc. * Tokens generated through a [[cryptographic algorithm]]
There are three types of decentralized applications:<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name="ruth"/> * Type I decentralized applications that have their own block chain, such as [[Bitcoin]]. * Type II decentralized applications that use the blockchain of a type I but are protocols and have tokens that are necessary for their function like the Bitcoin Omni Layer. * Type III decentralized applications that use the protocol of a type II and are additionally protocols that have tokens necessary for their function, such as the SAFE Network that uses the Omni Protocol to issue safecoins.
==Deployment== Decentralized applications may run on top of other cryptographic systems such as [[Ethereum]].{{r|coinwhat}} in December 2017, the popular game [[CryptoKitties]] slowed the Ethereum network and exposed the vulnerability of public blockchains to traffic slowdowns.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-04/cryptokitties-quickly-becomes-most-widely-used-ethereum-app |title=CryptoKitties Mania Overwhelms Ethereum Network's Processing |last= Kharif |first=Olga |date=2017-12-05 |work=Bloomberg |access-date=2018-08-23}}</ref> Decentralized applications use [[Smart contract|Smart Contracts]] to connect to a blockchain, where the backend of the Dapp runs on a decentralized [[P2P network]].<ref name="blockchainhub"/>
== Examples == <!-- Examples should be notable, ie. with a Wikipedia entry --> * [[Augur (software)|Augur]] - prediction market * [[Basic Attention Token]] - digital advertising network * [[Cryptokitties]] - [[Blockchain game|blockchain based virtual game]] * [[OmiseGO]] - open payment platform and decentralized exchange
==References== {{reflist|refs= <ref name=coinwhat>{{cite web|url=https://www.coindesk.com/information/what-is-a-decentralized-application-dapp/|title=What is a Decentralized Application?|last=Hertig|first=Alyssa}}</ref>
<ref name="sr">{{cite book|last1=Raval|first1=Siraj|title=Decentralized Applications HARNESSING BITCOIN'S BLOCKCHAIN TECHNOLOGY|publisher=O'Reilly|isbn=9781491924549}}</ref> }}
